/* Initializations.gau.  
Contains set_paramsAndGrids function which is shared by minwageDP as well as minwageDP_2 
and possibly other code.  The function initializes parameters and grids.  
Note that any file that calls setParams_grids() needs to declare all the variables it wants initialized, 
e.g. with code like "beta=0;".  
Note that this is _not_ a standalone file, as it does not initialize the variables it needs outside setParams_grids
itself, so it probably won't run by itself.  
*/


/* set_paramsAndGrids():
--SettingsSwitch options:

In order of appearance in Table 8, the runs are:
   67, 72, 73, 74, 75, 76, 77, 80, 81

For each version above, settingsSwitch
  XX.1 is for hikeStart=16  (i.e. 16 qtrs after age 18 --> age 22)
  XX.2 is for hikeStart=64  (age 34)
  XX.3 is for hikeStart=128 (age 50)

--hikeSwitch options: 0 means no hike, 1 means appropriate hike happens.  Note the actual hike def'n is unchanged 

--Baseline 67 takes about 36 hours to run, for each age of the wage hike, due to the extra fine grids
--Run 72 takes about 24 hours per hikeage, due to the extra fine grids
--All other runs use a coarser grid, and take 2-6 hours to run per hikeage
*/


/* This is the discretization of the state and choice variables.  
--DP interpolates _on_ state vars to get max utility.
--Simulation allows values within this grid to be chosen
*/

//Note: Setting values too small makes precision an issue.  (very small, e.g. set delta, theta to .0001 or .00001)


/* Some comments: 
--I think Sstates should always begin with zero.  This will probably be a requirement for the C-code.
So we don't have to check that S is on the sgrid.
With slightly less force,the same is probably true for Idecs, although if you want to implement a nonzero Ifloor
that makes some sense (who's to say how a sim wants to distribute the $$ the govt gives it).
--The c-code never checks if you run off the bottom of the A grid.  this is fine as long as R and pigrowthR are 
acceptably set.  if pigrowthR is too small and R too large then income can end up being negative which could be bad.
So make sure that Y is never negative (requires checking getIncome (pigrowthR), Astates, and R).
*/

/*
Note: Idecs MUST have zero as an element.  Am starting to incorporate negative I values, but zero must be on grid. 
The "ifloor" is implemented actually as an "sfloor".  There is no ifloor.  Expenditure floor is the 2-tuple (Cfloor,0).
The first element of Cdecs is defined to be the Cfloor (paid by  govt) (with I==0).
It is recommended that Sstates have its first element be zero.  and possibly the same for Cdecs (cfloor==0).
*/


//There are two important questions to ask when you calibrate the grids:
//  1) around periods t==wagehike +/- 10, how fine do i need the grids
//  2) what are the max/mins for the 4 relevant grids.




proc(30) = set_paramsAndGrids(settingsSwitch, hikeSwitch);
    local upper_lev, lower_lev, c, oddNumTSvals, minAssets, maxAssets, lowStock, maxStock, 
        highInvestment, highConsumption, 
        Cinc, Iinc, Aincr, Sincr, Iguess, Cguess, minAssets2, midStockL, midStockH, lowInvestment, lowInvestment2,
        newClow, newChigh, 
        numIdecs, numCdecs,
        logSD_TS, 
        lowConsumption, //standardize this ..
        Cfloor, Ifloor, //Cfloor is _not_ returned; it is defined to be the lowest value of Cdec grid.
        Iinc1,Iinc2, Iinc3, highInvestment1, highInvestment2, highInvestment3, highStock1, highStock2, highStock3,         Sincr1, Sincr2, Sincr3, //for grids of varying fineness.
        highConsumption1, highConsumption2, highConsumption3, Cinc1, Cinc2, Cinc3,
        transMtester,
//and these are the values to be returned:
    rho, R, beta, theta, PIgrowthR, incomeLevelAtHike, downpaymentR, delta, fixedDurableCost, numPIstates, 
    transitionM, PIstates, TSprobabilities, TSvals, Tstates, hikeStart, wageIncr, hikeLength, 
    wageHike, PIgrowthChangeTime, AfloorFnVersion, Cdec, Idec, Astates, Sstates, 
    CadjustmentLow, CadjustmentHigh, IadjustmentLow, IadjustmentHigh, IzeroIdxGAUSS, gridScale, sse, ssu, 
    rho_paper, adjustmentterm, timeadjustment, initialPI, newSlope;
    

 

    if ( settingsSwitch == 67.1);
    // BASELINE       extra fine grids

        hikeStart = 16;           // hikeStart is the first time at which the wagehike occurs
        rho=2;                    // CRRA  Gamma in Table 1

        beta= 0.93^(1/4);         // discount rate. ==4th root of .95   

        theta=.15;                // cobb-douglas exponent   (consumpt^(1-theta))*(stock^ theta) 
        PIgrowthR = 0.0108;       // Income Growth Rate (per quarter)
        downpaymentR = .4;        // downpayment rate
        delta= 0.034;             // depreciation rate of durables.
        R = 1.03^(1/4);           // 1+ rate of return.    
        fixedDurableCost = 0;     // multiplier on todays stock to determine fixed cost of buying a car/house (ie I>0)

    
        numPIstates = 7; 

        transitionM=0;
        PIstates=0;               // note: here, a PI state is an AR(1) shock - like a raise, not permanent income)
        c=0;

        sse = .005;               // Sigma squared e (VAR AR1)
        ssu = .05;                // Sigma squared u  (Trans comp)
        rho_paper = .995;         // rho as defined in the paper

        adjustmentterm = (ssu + sse/(1-rho_paper^2))/2;

//CAREFUL HERE!   

        upper_lev=0.07;   //as these get appropriately low, grids will NEED to be expanded
        lower_lev=0.07;    

        // rho_paper is rho in table 7
        // sse is sigma squared epsilon in table 7
        {transitionM,PIstates,c}=tauch(sse^(1/2), rho_paper, numPIstates, upper_lev, lower_lev);//units are  logged, additive.
        //transitionM = eye(numPIstates);
        //"No variability!";


        oddNumTSvals=7;   // I prefer to keep this number odd (hence the name) so as to have 0 be a TSval
        if ( round(oddNumTSvals/2) == oddNumTSvals/2);  
           print "oddNumTSvals isn't an odd number. it is " oddNumTSvals " Odd numbers allow exp(0)=1 to be an option. Comment this out if you want to keep your value. ending"; 
        end; endif;
        // ssu is sigma squared u in table 7
        logSD_TS = ssu^(1/2); // .34928=.122^1/2


//! careful, .05 v .01!
        {TSprobabilities, TSvals, c} = tauch(logSD_TS, 0, oddNumTSvals, .05, .05); //units are NOT logged, additive.        
//!
        TSprobabilities = TSprobabilities[1,.]'; // all rows are identical, since the correlation coeff was set to zero
        TSvals = exp(TSvals);

Tsvals = 1;
TSprobabilities=1;



incomeLevelAtHike = exp(ln(3.6)-adjustmentterm ); //getincome still expects this, but it doesn't get used;

        
        initialPI = 0.44;
        wageIncr= ln(1.0835); // will get us $250 
        hikeLength = 10; //hikeLength is the number of (consecutive) time periods for which the hike is nonzero (e.g. the length of the wageHike vector)
        Cfloor = .1;
        PIgrowthChangeTime = 81; // Time (State var!) at which PIgrowthR changes.
        AfloorFnVersion = 0;    //0 is paper's model.  1 is "no borrowing constraints", i.e. assets>=0 at death is only constraint.

//1/5, 1/9 not good enough [can loko at sims and see lots of cases where one goes down by max and hten goes down more next time].
//seem to be such that you can always get where you want to be after 2 periods, though.  
        Iguess = 1/7; //on at least semifine one run, going from 1/4, 1/8 to  1/12, 1/24 gave identical results
        Cguess = 1/11; // in general need way more cdecs than idecs.  and need a broader range of idecs than cdecs


        Tstates = seqa(1, 1, 188);     //T goes from 1 to periods/numTstates; functions require this 
                                       // A sim-person makes (periods-1) decisions in all, and has periods states. 
                                       // end of final period is certain death e.g. last dec should be "eat all" */     
        Astates = setGrid(-180|-35|-10|10|30|150, 8|.55|.35|1.5|7);  //COH states, actually! 
                                                                    //-31 was min for 4ksims for 1.27001_agrideror 
                                                                    //the states from 30 to 150 shoudl be very coarse, just for initial sims that are super high.
        Sstates = setGrid(.3|2|7|25|50|90|220, .2|.25|.25|.7|4|8);  // 15 to 40 seems to be the range everyone is in around period 30; 
        Cdec = setGrid(Cfloor|2|4|18|27, .05|.05|.05|.5);   //1.27 had max cons of 22, 4k sims.
        Idec = setGrid(0|2|4|7|14|20, .05|.05|.05|.4|.5);   //top of igrid pretty rare
        gridScale=1000;

        numCdecs = rows(Cdec); 
        numIdecs = rows(Idec);
        CadjustmentLow = floor(Cguess*numCdecs);
        CadjustmentHigh = ceil(Cguess*numCdecs);
        IadjustmentLow = floor(Iguess*numIdecs);
        IadjustmentHigh = ceil(Iguess*numIdecs);

    elseif ( settingsSwitch == 67.2);
    // BASELINE    ,   extra fine grids

        hikeStart = 64;           //hikeStart is the first time at which the wagehike occurs
        rho=2;                    // CRRA  Gamma in Table 1

        beta= 0.93^(1/4);         // discount rate. ==4th root of .95   

        theta=.15;                // cobb-douglas exponent   (consumpt^(1-theta))*(stock^ theta) 
        PIgrowthR = 0.0108;       // Income Growth Rate (per quarter)
        downpaymentR = .4;        // downpayment rate
        delta= 0.034;             // depreciation rate of durables.
        R = 1.03^(1/4);           // 1+ rate of return.    
        fixedDurableCost = 0;     // multiplier on todays stock to determine fixed cost of buying a car/house (ie I>0)

    
        numPIstates = 7; 

        transitionM=0;
        PIstates=0;               // note: here, a PI state is an AR(1) shock - like a raise, not permanent income)
        c=0;
 
        sse = .005;               // Sigma squared e (VAR AR1)
        ssu = .05;                // Sigma squared u  (Trans comp)
        rho_paper = .995;         // rho as defined in the paper

        adjustmentterm = (ssu + sse/(1-rho_paper^2))/2;

//CAREFUL HERE!   

        upper_lev=0.07;   //as these get appropriately low, grids will NEED to be expanded
        lower_lev=0.07;    

        // rho_paper is rho in table 7
        // sse is sigma squared epsilon in table 7
        {transitionM,PIstates,c}=tauch(sse^(1/2), rho_paper, numPIstates, upper_lev, lower_lev);//units are  logged, additive.
        //transitionM = eye(numPIstates);
        //"No variability!";


        oddNumTSvals=7;   // I prefer to keep this number odd (hence the name) so as to have 0 be a TSval
        if ( round(oddNumTSvals/2) == oddNumTSvals/2);  
           print "oddNumTSvals isn't an odd number. it is " oddNumTSvals " Odd numbers allow exp(0)=1 to be an option. Comment this out if you want to keep your value. ending"; 
        end; endif;
        // ssu is sigma squared u in table 7
        logSD_TS = ssu^(1/2); // .34928=.122^1/2


//! careful, .05 v .01!
        {TSprobabilities, TSvals, c} = tauch(logSD_TS, 0, oddNumTSvals, .05, .05); //units are NOT logged, additive.        
//!
        TSprobabilities = TSprobabilities[1,.]'; // all rows are identical, since the correlation coeff was set to zero
        TSvals = exp(TSvals);

Tsvals = 1;
TSprobabilities=1;



incomeLevelAtHike = exp(ln(3.6)-adjustmentterm ); //getincome still expects this, but it doesn't get used;

        
        initialPI = 0.44;
        wageIncr= ln(1.0517); // will get us $250 
        hikeLength = 10; //hikeLength is the number of (consecutive) time periods for which the hike is nonzero (e.g. the length of the wageHike vector)
        Cfloor = .1;
        PIgrowthChangeTime = 81; // Time (State var!) at which PIgrowthR changes.
        AfloorFnVersion = 0;    //0 is paper's model.  1 is "no borrowing constraints", i.e. assets>=0 at death is only constraint.

//1/5, 1/9 not good enough [can loko at sims and see lots of cases where one goes down by max and hten goes down more next time].
//seem to be such that you can always get where you want to be after 2 periods, though.  
        Iguess = 1/7; //on at least semifine one run, going from 1/4, 1/8 to  1/12, 1/24 gave identical results
        Cguess = 1/11; // in general need way more cdecs than idecs.  and need a broader range of idecs than cdecs


        Tstates = seqa(1, 1, 188);     //T goes from 1 to periods/numTstates; functions require this 
                                       // A sim-person makes (periods-1) decisions in all, and has periods states. 
                                       // end of final period is certain death e.g. last dec should be "eat all" */     
        Astates = setGrid(-180|-35|-10|10|30|150, 8|.55|.35|1.5|7);  //COH states, actually! 
                                                                    //-31 was min for 4ksims for 1.27001_agrideror 
                                                                    //the states from 30 to 150 shoudl be very coarse, just for initial sims that are super high.
        Sstates = setGrid(.3|2|7|25|50|90|220, .2|.25|.25|.7|4|8);  // 15 to 40 seems to be the range everyone is in around period 30; 
        Cdec = setGrid(Cfloor|2|4|18|27, .05|.05|.05|.5);   //1.27 had max cons of 22, 4k sims.
        Idec = setGrid(0|2|4|7|14|20, .05|.05|.05|.4|.5);   //top of igrid pretty rare
        gridScale=1000;

        numCdecs = rows(Cdec); 
        numIdecs = rows(Idec);
        CadjustmentLow = floor(Cguess*numCdecs);
        CadjustmentHigh = ceil(Cguess*numCdecs);
        IadjustmentLow = floor(Iguess*numIdecs);
        IadjustmentHigh = ceil(Iguess*numIdecs);



    elseif ( settingsSwitch == 67.3);
    // BASELINE    ,   extra fine grids

        hikeStart = 128;          //hikeStart is the first time at which the wagehike occurs
        rho=2;                    // CRRA  Gamma in Table 1

        beta= 0.93^(1/4);         // discount rate. ==4th root of .95   

        theta=.15;                // cobb-douglas exponent   (consumpt^(1-theta))*(stock^ theta) 
        PIgrowthR = 0.0108;       // Income Growth Rate (per quarter)
        downpaymentR = .4;        // downpayment rate
        delta= 0.034;             // depreciation rate of durables.
        R = 1.03^(1/4);           // 1+ rate of return.    
        fixedDurableCost = 0;     // multiplier on todays stock to determine fixed cost of buying a car/house (ie I>0)

    
        numPIstates = 7; 

        transitionM=0;
        PIstates=0;               // note: here, a PI state is an AR(1) shock - like a raise, not permanent income)
        c=0;

        sse = .005;               // Sigma squared e (VAR AR1)
        ssu = 0.05;               // Sigma squared u  (Trans comp)
        rho_paper = .995;         // rho as defined in the paper

        adjustmentterm = (ssu + sse/(1-rho_paper^2))/2;

//CAREFUL HERE!   

        upper_lev=0.07;   //as these get appropriately low, grids will NEED to be expanded
        lower_lev=0.07;    

        // rho_paper is rho in table 7
        // sse is sigma squared epsilon in table 7
        {transitionM,PIstates,c}=tauch(sse^(1/2), rho_paper, numPIstates, upper_lev, lower_lev);//units are  logged, additive.
        //transitionM = eye(numPIstates);
        //"No variability!";


        oddNumTSvals=7;    // I prefer to keep this number odd (hence the name) so as to have 0 be a TSval
        if ( round(oddNumTSvals/2) == oddNumTSvals/2);  
           print "oddNumTSvals isn't an odd number. it is " oddNumTSvals " Odd numbers allow exp(0)=1 to be an option. Comment this out if you want to keep your value. ending"; 
        end; endif;
        // ssu is sigma squared u in table 7
        logSD_TS = ssu^(1/2); // .34928=.122^1/2


//! careful, .05 v .01!
        {TSprobabilities, TSvals, c} = tauch(logSD_TS, 0, oddNumTSvals, .05, .05); //units are NOT logged, additive.        
//!
        TSprobabilities = TSprobabilities[1,.]'; // all rows are identical, since the correlation coeff was set to zero
        TSvals = exp(TSvals);

Tsvals = 1;
TSprobabilities=1;



incomeLevelAtHike = exp(ln(3.6)-adjustmentterm ); //getincome still expects this, but it doesn't get used;

        
        initialPI = 0.44;
        wageIncr= ln(1.0457); // will get us $250 
        hikeLength = 10; //hikeLength is the number of (consecutive) time periods for which the hike is nonzero (e.g. the length of the wageHike vector)
        Cfloor = .1;
        PIgrowthChangeTime = 81; // Time (State var!) at which PIgrowthR changes.
        AfloorFnVersion = 0;    //0 is paper's model.  1 is "no borrowing constraints", i.e. assets>=0 at death is only constraint.

//1/5, 1/9 not good enough [can loko at sims and see lots of cases where one goes down by max and hten goes down more next time].
//seem to be such that you can always get where you want to be after 2 periods, though.  
        Iguess = 1/7; //on at least semifine one run, going from 1/4, 1/8 to  1/12, 1/24 gave identical results
        Cguess = 1/11; // in general need way more cdecs than idecs.  and need a broader range of idecs than cdecs


        Tstates = seqa(1, 1, 188);     //T goes from 1 to periods/numTstates; functions require this 
                                       // A sim-person makes (periods-1) decisions in all, and has periods states. 
                                       // end of final period is certain death e.g. last dec should be "eat all" */     
        Astates = setGrid(-180|-35|-10|10|30|150, 8|.55|.35|1.5|7);  //COH states, actually! 
                                                                    //-31 was min for 4ksims for 1.27001_agrideror 
                                                                    //the states from 30 to 150 shoudl be very coarse, just for initial sims that are super high.
        Sstates = setGrid(.3|2|7|25|50|90|220, .2|.25|.25|.7|4|8);  // 15 to 40 seems to be the range everyone is in around period 30; 
        Cdec = setGrid(Cfloor|2|4|18|27, .05|.05|.05|.5);   //1.27 had max cons of 22, 4k sims.
        Idec = setGrid(0|2|4|7|14|20, .05|.05|.05|.4|.5);   //top of igrid pretty rare
        gridScale=1000;

        numCdecs = rows(Cdec); 
        numIdecs = rows(Idec);
        CadjustmentLow = floor(Cguess*numCdecs);
        CadjustmentHigh = ceil(Cguess*numCdecs);
        IadjustmentLow = floor(Iguess*numIdecs);
        IadjustmentHigh = ceil(Iguess*numIdecs);




    elseif ( settingsSwitch == 72.1);
    //Differences from baseline:  downpayment=1,  (Note, grids are extra fine, as in baseline)

        hikeStart = 16;           //hikeStart is the first time at which the wagehike occurs
        rho=2;                    // CRRA  Gamma in Table 1

        beta= 0.93^(1/4);         // discount rate. ==4th root of .95   

        theta=.15;                // cobb-douglas exponent   (consumpt^(1-theta))*(stock^ theta) 
        PIgrowthR = 0.0108;       // Income Growth Rate (per quarter)
        downpaymentR = 1;        // downpayment rate
        delta= 0.034;             // depreciation rate of durables.
        R = 1.03^(1/4);           // 1+ rate of return.    
        fixedDurableCost = 0;     // multiplier on todays stock to determine fixed cost of buying a car/house (ie I>0)

    
        numPIstates = 7; 

        transitionM=0;
        PIstates=0;             // note: here, a PI state is an AR(1) shock - like a raise, not permanent income)
        c=0;

        sse = .005;       // Sigma squared e (VAR AR1)
        ssu = .05;          // Sigma squared u  (Trans comp)
        rho_paper = .995; // rho as defined in the paper

        adjustmentterm = (ssu + sse/(1-rho_paper^2))/2;

//CAREFUL HERE!   

        upper_lev=0.07;   //as these get appropriately low, grids will NEED to be expanded
        lower_lev=0.07;    

        // rho_paper is rho in table 7
        // sse is sigma squared epsilon in table 7
        {transitionM,PIstates,c}=tauch(sse^(1/2), rho_paper, numPIstates, upper_lev, lower_lev);//units are  logged, additive.
        //transitionM = eye(numPIstates);
        //"No variability!";


        oddNumTSvals=7;   // I prefer to keep this number odd (hence the name) so as to have 0 be a TSval
        if ( round(oddNumTSvals/2) == oddNumTSvals/2);  print "oddNumTSvals isn't an odd number. it is " oddNumTSvals " Odd numbers allow exp(0)=1 to be an option. Comment this out if you want to keep your value. ending"; end; endif;
        // ssu is sigma squared u in table 7
        logSD_TS = ssu^(1/2); // .34928=.122^1/2


//! careful, .05 v .01!
        {TSprobabilities, TSvals, c} = tauch(logSD_TS, 0, oddNumTSvals, .05, .05); //units are NOT logged, additive.        
//!
        TSprobabilities = TSprobabilities[1,.]'; // all rows are identical, since the correlation coeff was set to zero
        TSvals = exp(TSvals);

Tsvals = 1;
TSprobabilities=1;



incomeLevelAtHike = exp(ln(3.6)-adjustmentterm ); //getincome still expects this, but it doesn't get used;

        
        initialPI = 0.44;
        wageIncr= ln(1.0835); // will get us $250 
        hikeLength = 10; //hikeLength is the number of (consecutive) time periods for which the hike is nonzero (e.g. the length of the wageHike vector)
        Cfloor = .1;
        PIgrowthChangeTime = 81; // Time (State var!) at which PIgrowthR changes.
        AfloorFnVersion = 0;    //0 is paper's model.  1 is "no borrowing constraints", i.e. assets>=0 at death is only constraint.

//1/5, 1/9 not good enough [can loko at sims and see lots of cases where one goes down by max and hten goes down more next time].
//seem to be such that you can always get where you want to be after 2 periods, though.  
